    name: "o2-nodes-horns",
    svg: `<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path fill="#1f6b46" fill-rule="evenodd" d="M2 3 Q12 5.4 22 3 L22 5 L18.5 6 Q20.5 7.5 20.5 12.5 Q20.5 21.5 12 21.5 Q3.5 21.5 3.5 12.5 Q3.5 7.5 5.5 6 L2 5 Z M8 10.8 m2.7 0 a2.7 2.7 0 1 1 -5.4 0 a2.7 2.7 0 1 1 5.4 0 Z M16 10.8 m2.7 0 a2.7 2.7 0 1 1 -5.4 0 a2.7 2.7 0 1 1 5.4 0 Z M12 13.8 L14.5 16.6 L12 19.4 L9.5 16.6 Z"/></svg>`,
    rationale: "Tufts become short horizontal horns (2-unit-thick bands sweeping outward to the frame edges) over a round body, the great-horned-owl silhouette. Horizontal horns are the one tuft orientation cats never have, and with node eyes plus a 5x5.6 diamond beak the owl read survives cleanly down to 14px.",
